<DOC><DOCNO> AP891013-0191 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2104EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-BusinessHighlights     10-13 0869</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0906</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A failing airline buyout knocked the stockmarket off its record-setting pace with a sudden dive that erasedmore than 190 points from the Dow Jones industrial average andconjured memories of the 1987 crash.   Nearly $200 billion was wiped out from the paper value of stocksas more than 250 million shares changed hands on Friday.   Over 100 million shares were traded in the last hour followingan announcement that the employee-led, highly leveraged buyout ofUnited Airlines parent UAL Corp. had come unglued.   The widely watched Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocksplunged 190.58 points to 2,569.26, the biggest point drop since thecrash of 1987.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Junk bond prices plunged as financing problemsfor a major airline buyout widened fears over a possible collapseof the slumping $200 billion market of the high-yield securities.   News that bidders had failed to raise financing for the planned$6.75 billion buyout of UAL Corp. also spread panic Friday thatbillions of dollars in other planned debt-financed deals would haveto be scrapped.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stock-index futures trading on the ChicagoMercantile Exchange was halted twice as tumbling stock pricestriggered ``circuit breakers'' designed to prevent a rapid,computer-driven collapse.   The action Friday was the first time the market had fallen farenough to trigger 30-minute halts in trading since the circuitbreakers were installed a year after the stock market's October1987 collapse.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The pilot-management group attempting to buy UALCorp. said it could not get financing for its $6.75 billion deal.   The group issued a statement Friday that banks managing thefinancing for the proposed $300 a share acquisition of the companyindicated they had not received sufficient commitments to completethe buyout at that price.   But the group _ which also includes British Airways PLC _ statedit expected to revise the proposal and continue its attempts to buythe airline.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A sharp rise in energy costs helped trigger arebound in wholesale price inflation in September, wiping out threerare monthly declines this summer, the government said.   The 0.9 percent increase Friday in the Labor Department'sProducer Price Index, measuring inflation one stop short of theretail level, represented a return to the high inflation ratesexperienced in the first five months of the year.   In another economic report, the Commerce Department said retailsales rose a stronger-than-expected 0.5 percent last month, theseventh consecutive rise.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A plunge in General Motors Corp. car and lighttruck sales led an 11.9 percent decline in early-October vehiclesales by domestic automakers compared with last year, the companiessaid.   The eight major companies making vehicles in North America saidFriday their cars and light trucks sold at an average rate of30,734 a day during the Oct. 1-10 period this year, compared with34,867 during the same time last year.</TEXT><DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Economic growth in 1990 will slump toits slowest pace in eight years with an outright recession adistinct threat unless the Federal Reserve lowers interest rates,the nation's top business executives forecast.   The Business Council, composed of the chief executives of 100 ofthe country's largest corporations, said Friday the economy beganto lose steam this summer. They predicted the sluggish period wouldlast through much of next year.</TEXT><DATELINE>CARBO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole set up thefirst face-to-face meeting between Pittston Coal Group Inc. and theUnited Mine Workers since a bitter strike began six months ago.   Mrs. Dole said Pittston Chairman Paul Douglas and UMW PresidentRichard Trumka agreed to meet with her Saturday in her Washingtonoffice. It would mark the first time any company and unionofficials have met directly since 1,695 miners in Virginia, WestVirginia and Kentucky went on strike April 5 against Pittston CoalGroup Inc.</TEXT><DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Young andamp; Rubicam, one of the nation'slargest advertising agencies, pleaded innocent to charges it paidnearly $1 million in bribes to Jamaican officials for the island'slucrative tourism campaign.   Two of the company's executives and a former executive alsopleaded innocent Friday in U.S. District Court Friday.   Young andamp; Rubicam faces up to $7.5 million in fines if it isconvicted. Young andamp; Rubicam still holds the Jamaica account, whichwon praise for its theme ``Come Back to Jamaica,'' and hasvigorously denied any wrongdoing.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The biggest selloff since the crash of 1987 rocked the stockmarket Friday, driving prices into a free-fall decline followingnews that a big buyout deal for UAL Corp. had fallen through. TheDow Jones average of 30 industrials plunged 190.58 points, or 6.91percent, to 2,569.26.   Currency dealers pounded down the dollar in hectic sellingincited by the stock plunge.   Bond prices rocketed higher in heavy trading afternoon asinvestors fled the panicky stock market.   Tumbling stock prices triggered temporary trading halts forstock-index futures on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, in a dropthat mirrored a near-record selloff on Wall Street; orange juicefutures plunged; and crude oil futures jumped higher.</TEXT></DOC>